the industry during this transformative moment. Drawing from five years of extensive interviews with female producers, writers, and directors at different stages of their careers, Courtney Brannon Donoghue examines how Hollywood business cultures “value” female-driven projects as risky or not bankable. Industry claims that “movies targeting female audiences don’t make money” or “women can’t direct big-budget blockbusters” have long circulated to rationalize systemic gender inequities and have served to normalize studios prioritizing the white male–driven status quo. Through a critical media industry studies lens, The Value Gap challenges this pervasive logic with firsthand accounts of women actively navigating the male-dominated and conglomerate-owned industrial landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion picture authorshipxSocial aspects. 0aMotion picture industryxSocial aspects. 0aMotion picturesxDistributionxSocial aspects. 0aMotion picturesxProduction and directionxSocial aspects. 0aWomen in the motion picture industryxSocial conditions. 0aWomen motion picture producers and directorsxSocial conditions. 0aWomen screenwritersxSocial conditions. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  aGender equity and inclusion, contemporary film industry, Conglomerate Hollywood, women filmmakers, gender and the workplace, production cultures, distribution cultures, gendered value, media industry studies, industry interviews, above-the-line workers.  afemale directors, female screenwriters, female producers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079782440uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32729640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477327319423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477327319/original  a978-3-11-0797